pean empire and the murky position it occupied between the Old and New Worlds to slavery and diasporas. How was the stability of the old regimes undermined? Which mechanisms of successful popular mobilization can be observed? What roles did blacks and Indians play? Drawing on both primary documents and extant secondary literature to answer these questions, Wim Klooster portrays the revolutions as parallel and connected uprisings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aRevolutionsvCross-cultural studies. 0aRevolutionszAmericaxHistoryy18th century. 0aRevolutionszAmericaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSovereigntyvCross-cultural studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aAtlantic.  aDiaspora.  aEuropean.  aRevolutions.  aWorld.  abetween.  acentral.  acomparative.  aconcept.  aempire.  afield.  afrom.  ahistory.  alens.  amurky.  aoccupied.  aposition.  areveal.  aseveral.  aslavery.  athemes.  awields.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814749098.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814749098423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814749098/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK